The paper describes a probabilistic framework for synthesizing control policies for multi-robot systems, which involves decision-making under uncertainty and coordination among agents. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of Multiagent Systems (cs.MA), which deals with the study of systems composed of multiple interacting intelligent agents. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of Decentralized, partially observable Markov decision processes (Dec-POMDPs), which are a type of decision-making model commonly used in Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Robotics (cs.RO) for multi-agent systems. The paper also discusses the use of macro-actions, which are a type of planning technique used in control systems (cs.SY) to simplify the decision-making process. Finally, the paper uses a probabilistic framework, which involves the use of probability theory and statistical methods, suggesting that it may also belong to the sub-category of Machine Learning (cs.LG).
